            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">This is one of IA’s earliest works, written in four days
                     during a visit to his friend al-Mawrūrī in the village of Moron in Andalusia.
                     It was inspired by Sirr al-Asrār (The Secrets of Secrets) by pseudo-Aristotle
                     concerning the nature of government, with IA adding a spiritual dimension to
                     the discussion. In 21 chapters, it explains the correspondences between the
                     external political hierarchy of princes and rulers, and the inner rulership of
                     the spirit within the human being.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by at least three historic mss.
                  The best is probably Leiden Or 86, written possibly in 606H. Also Corum 756 (part
                  1) and Yusuf Ağa 4859 (part 2) from SQ’s library, which were originally the same
                  document, undated. Yusuf Aga 4859 was stolen but a copy exists on digitised
                  microfilm. Koprulu 713 seems to be a complete copy of this original dated 663H. OY
                  also lists four commentaries, including one by al-Dāmūnī (d. 1199/1785).</note>
